        outline: "The immune system is essential not only for fighting infections but also for helping the body repair damaged tissues. To work effectively, it relies on a delicate balance between different organs, cells, and signalling molecules. One important group of cells involved in maintaining this balance is regulatory B cells (Bregs). These cells help control immune responses and prevent excessive inflammation that could harm the body. Recent studies have shown that there are several types of regulatory B cells, each with unique characteristics and functions, including but not limited to IL-10-producing Bregs, granzyme B-expressing Bregs, and Bregs characterized by specific surface markers such as CD1d and CD5. However, it is still unclear what signals cause B cells to become these different subtypes, and whether each subtype plays a distinct role in the immune system. This project will explore: • What signals drive the differentiation of B cells into various regulatory subtypes. • How the functions of these subtypes differ, especially in terms of controlling immune responses and supporting tissue repair. By investigating these questions, the project aims to improve our understanding of how regulatory B cells contribute to immune balance. This knowledge could eventually help in designing better treatments for autoimmune diseases, chronic inflammation, and other immune-related conditions.",
