        students: "4",
        aim: "This project will explore the role of hypoxia in cardiovascular immunology. A selection of the project aims will be to investigate: (1) How low oxygen conditions can influence proliferative vascular signalling (2) Explore how exosomes act as mediators and biomarkers of hypoxic signalling (3) Evaluate the role of hypoxia in COVID-19-related cardiovascular complications and further assess therapeutic strategies. Note: Project available to multiple students, with specific aims being tailored and advanced throughout the research based on each student's interest and independent exploration.",
        outline: "Cardiovascular diseases (CVD) and cancer are among the leading causes of global mortality. The complex pathomechanisms of these diseases are multifactorial and are influenced by various genetic, environmental, and lifestyle factors. A critical contributor to both conditions is hypoxia, defined as inadequate oxygen availability, which impacts multiple biological processes associated with disease progression. Hypoxia is known to drive hyperproliferative responses and plays a pivotal role triggering a cascade of cellular responses, primarily through the activation of hypoxia-inducible factors (HIFs). Hypoxia influences proliferative vascular signalling, contributing to detrimental vascular remodelling and inflammation. Furthermore, exosomes (small vesicles released from cells) have emerged as key mediators of hypoxic signalling, serving as biomarkers of disease and active communicators in the tumour microenvironment. Understanding these hypoxic mechanisms will help evaluate therapeutic strategies aimed at mitigating CVD and cancer complications.",
