        aim: "This project is aimed in developing polymeric film substrates for IJP of pharmaceuticals and the specific project objectives would be 1. Quality by Design studies on optimising polymeric film former (pullulan, HPMC/HPC, maltodextrin) and plasticiser (glycerol, polyethylene glycol, polyvinyl alcohol and mixtures) composition for producing films that can be used for IJP. (Week 6-7) 2. Preparation of films with solvent casting or lyophilisation (Week 8-9) 3. Characterise polymeric films in terms of appearance (ASTM Method D1746-92/Camera), thickness, mechanical strength (texture analysis), flexibility, disintegration time and compatibility with inkjet printing. (Week 10) 4. Inkjet printing of dye/antimicrobials orodispersible films and characterisation in terms of dye/antimicrobial loading (UV/Fluorescence) mechanical strength, disintegration time. (Week 11)",
        outline: "The current manufacturing model of medicines relies on mass production of large batches with a limited number of doses. However, this approach overlooks interindividual factors between patients resulting in variations in the therapeutic response and potential inefficacy or toxicity reactions. Reports suggest that 40-70% prescribed medications are ineffective and 1 in 15 hospital admissions are in relation to adverse drug effects resulting from inadequate doses. There is growing need for a more personalised medicine approach taking into account individual needs and complexity of diseases towards developing new pharmaceutical forms. Additive manufacturing technologies such as 3D printing and inkjet printing (IJP) are emerging as alternative methods towards personalised medicines. IJP technology is characterised by high precision in pharmaceutical ink deposition, avoiding contact with the substrate and allowing for accurate control of the printed dose based on the volume ejected through the nozzle. Additionally, IJP offers great flexibility in terms of substrate as formulated inks can be printed onto a wide variety of materials including films, stents, contact lenses, nails. Orodispersible films (ODFs) are ultra-thin, stamp-sized, elegant, portable and patient-centric pharmaceutical dosage forms that do not need water to be ingested. They are particularly useful for paediatric and geriatric patient populations with special needs such as dysphagia, Parkinson’s disease, while they can be used for topical delivery of antimicrobials and anti-inflammatory drugs to dental cavities or oral mucosa for a local application. IJP technology can be an alternatively to currently manufacturing method and allow facile and cost-effective manufacture of these dosage forms. IJP of orodispersible films requires the development of a film substrate with appropriate characteristics for printing and the use of a pharmaceutical ink that contains the active pharmaceutical ingredient.",
